ion Film of the Deutsche Kinemathek – Museum für Film und Fernsehen -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile scholars recognize both museums and films as sites where historical knowledge and cultural memory are created, the convergence between their methods of constructing the past has only recently been acknowledged. The essays in Exhibiting the German Past examine a range of films, museums, and experiences which blend the two, considering how authentic objects and cinematic techniques are increasingly used in similar ways by both visual media and museums.This is the first collection to focus on the museum–film connection in German-language culture and the first to approach the issue using the concept of “musealization,” a process that, because it engages the cultural destruction wrought by modernization, offers new means of constructing historical knowledge and shaping collective memory within and beyond the museum’s walls. Featuring a wide range of valuable case studies, Exhibiting the German Past offers a unique perspective on the developing relationship between museums and visual media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCollective memoryzGermany. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszGermany. 0aMuseum exhibitsxSocial aspectszGermany. 0aMuseumsxSocial aspectszGermany. 7aART / General.2bisacsh1 aBach, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFirth, Catriona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFloyd, Kathryn M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaeger, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuzniar, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc